  "articleSummary": "The article critiques the common practice of using a fixed dropdown (e.g., P1–P4) for task priority in project management tools like Jira, arguing it creates an inflationary \"priority trap\" that leads to absurd labels like P00 and \"engineering theater.\" Its core thesis is that priority is fluid and multidimensional, requiring dynamic or unbounded systems (e.g., neutral starting values, MoSCoW, composite scores) rather than static choices. The tone blends humorous rant with analytical tutorial, using recurring metaphors such as the \"z-index war\" (where priorities escalate like CSS z-index) and the \"backlog as Bizzaro Trophy Room\" to illustrate the absurdity of rigid prioritization. Intended for developers, Jira admins, and engineering leaders, the article advocates for realistic backlog management and discarding outdated tickets.",
